The paper discusses the use of Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning (GAIL) for simulating driving scenarios with multiple agents. This involves training a model to imitate the behavior of human drivers in a multi-agent setting. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), which is the primary focus of the paper. The paper also involves aspects of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Robotics (cs.RO) since it deals with autonomous vehicles. Computer Vision (cs.CV) is also relevant since the simulation involves visual perception. Finally, the paper involves aspects of Systems and Control (cs.SY) since it deals with controlling the behavior of multiple agents in a complex environment.
